as an illness in need of curing. It is this "pathology" that Nietzsche called nihilism. Arguing that this insight lies at the core of Nietzsche's philosophy as a whole, Michalski seeks to explain and reinterpret Nietzsche's thought in light of it. Michalski maintains that many of Nietzsche's main ideas--including his views on love, morality (beyond good and evil), the will to power, overcoming, the suprahuman (or the overman, as it is infamously referred to), the Death of God, and the myth of the eternal return--take on new meaning and significance when viewed through the prism of eternity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aEternal return. 0aEternity. 0aPHILOSOPHYvGeneral. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aApocalypse.  aGospel of Matthew.  aJesus Christ.  aNietzsche.  aPhaedo.  aPlato.  aSocrates.  aZarathustra.  achance.  achild at play.  aconcepts.  acontemporary culture.  adeath.  adeception.  adiversification.  adivinity.  aenvy.  aeternal love.  aeternity.  aevil.  afalsehood.  afire.  agood.  agrazing cows.  aguilt.  ahistory.  ahuman certainty.  ahuman condition.  ahuman life.  ahuman nature.  ahumanity.  aknowledge.  alife.  alived moment.  alove.  amemory.  amodern science.  amoral concepts.  amorality.  amorals.  anecessity.  anegation of life.  anihilism.  anihilistic culture.  aoverman.  apassing.  apeace.  aphilosophy.  apower.  arationality.  areason.  arejection.  arelativistic culture.  ascience.  aserenity.  asuprahuman.  atime.  awill to power.1 aPaloff, Benjamin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400840212zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://